'''Ji Wallace''' (born 23 June 1977 in [[Lismore, Victoria|Lismore]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]) is an [[Australia]]n [[trampoline gymnast]] and Olympic silver medalist.

Earlier in his career Wallace won several Australian national titles and made an international breakthrough in 1996 by winning gold in the DMT (double mini trampoline) discipline at the 19th Trampoline World Championships in Vancouver.<ref name="worlds1996">{{cite web|url=http://www.trampoline.co.uk/worlds/Historic/worlds%201996.pdf|title=1996 World Championships Results|accessdate=2008-09-30}}</ref>

In the world championships held in Sydney, he set a world record for completing a jump with the highest [[degree of difficulty]] in the DMT, a triple-triple.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}

He competed at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in [[Sydney]], where he received a silver medal in [[trampoline]].<ref name=db-ol-GYM2000>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=25&sp=GYM "2000 Summer Olympics &ndash; Sydney, Australia &ndash; Gymnastics"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823081053/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=25&sp=GYM |date=2008-08-23 }} ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on 15 August 2008)</ref>
<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2000/gymnastics/news/2000/09/23/mens_tramopline_ap CNN/SI report on the trampolin final]</ref>

In 2005, he [[Coming out|came out]] publicly as [[gay]],<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/sport/ji-talking-on-highs-lows-and-a-super-new-move/2007/06/09/1181089387102.html Interview with "Sydney Morning Herald"]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/news/local/2489/Out-And-Proud-Diver-Makes-A-Splash.htm |title=Out And Proud Diver Makes A Splash on |publisher=[[Samesame.com.au]] |date=27 May 2008 |accessdate=12 December 2014 |first=Travis |last=de Jonk |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230453/http://www.samesame.com.au/news/local/2489/Out-And-Proud-Diver-Makes-A-Splash.htm |archivedate= 3 March 2016 |df= }}</ref> and was the first Australian to be named a Gay Games Ambassador.<ref>[http://www.gaygames.com/en/participants/ambassadors/wallace.htm Federation of Gay Games player profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924071115/http://www.gaygames.com/en/participants/ambassadors/wallace.htm |date=2008-09-24 }}</ref> In an August 2012 letter to the ''[[Sydney Star Observer]]'', a gay-oriented weekly [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] newspaper, he revealed he is HIV-positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/australia-news/new-south-wales-news/2012/08/08/aussie-olympian-reveals-hiv-status/82378 |title=Aussie Olympian reveals HIV status &#124; Star Online |publisher=Starobserver.com.au |date=2012-08-08 |accessdate=2012-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Garcia |first=Michelle |url=http://hivplusmag.com/NewsStory.asp?id=22223&sd=08%2F08%2F2012 |title=Gay Olympian Comes Out as HIV-Positive |publisher=HIVPlusMag.com |date=2012-08-08 |accessdate=2012-10-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809053205/http://hivplusmag.com/NewsStory.asp?id=22223&sd=08%2F08%2F2012 |archivedate=2012-08-09 |df= }}</ref>

Wallace returned to his trampoline roots in order to qualify for the Beijing Olympics, but missed Olympic selection at the 2007 World Championships in QC Canada.

Wallace was a cast member with the [[Cirque du Soleil]] in their show [[ZAIA]] in Macau, China.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} In October 2008 while performing an acrobatic move Ji fell badly causing significant injuries; he spent 21 months rehabilitating his right ankle, successfully learning to walk again. In August 2010 he took a coaching job in Montreal at the Cirque du Soleil headquarters, but in 2012 returned to his native Australia,{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} where he is now head coach of Sky School. A trampoline program run by trampoline park chain "Sky Zone".

