{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} '''Olara A. Otunnu''' is a [[Uganda]]n politician, diplomat, and lawyer. He was President of the [[Uganda People's Congress]] (UPC), a political party, from 2010 to 2015 and stood as the party's candidate in the [[Ugandan general election, 2011|2011 presidential election]].<ref name="Control">Edris Kiggundu, [http://www.observer.ug/news-headlines/36673-how-otunnu-lost-control-of-upc "How Otunnu lost control of UPC"], ''The Observer'', 6 March 2015, accessed 29 June 2015.</ref> Otunnu was Uganda's [[Permanent Representative to the United Nations]] from 1980 to 1985 and served as [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Uganda)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1985 to 1986. Later, he was President of the [[International Peace Institute|International Peace Academy]] from 1990<ref name=Press>[https://www.un.org/press/en/1997/19971010.SGA655.html "Olara A. Otunnu (Cote d'Ivoire), Secretary-General's Special Representative for Children in Armed Conflict"], United Nations press release, SG/A/655, BIO/3110, 10 October 1997.</ref> to 1998,<ref>[http://sydney.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=36 "2005 Sydney Peace Prize awarded to United Nations Advocate for Children"], University of Sydney, 9 May 2005.</ref> and he was an [[Under-Secretary-General of the United Nations]] and Special Representative for Children and Armed Conflict from 1997<ref name=Press/> to 2005.<ref>[https://www.un.org/news/dh/pdf/english/2005/01082005.pdf "Annan compliments departing Olara Otunnu for raising profile of children in war"], ''UN Daily News'', issue DH/4447, 1 August 2005.</ref>
==Background== Otunnu was born in [[Mucwini]], among the Chua people of the Central Luo.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}
==Education== He received his early education at Mvara, Mucwini, and [[Anaka]] primary schools. He received his secondary education at Gulu High School and [[King's College Budo]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Profile: Olara Otunnu | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/1973735.stm | work=BBC: Profiles. | publisher=BBC News | accessdate=19 July 2012 | authorlink=Profile: Olara Otunnu | archiveurl=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/1973735.stm | archivedate=8 May 2002}}</ref> He then attended [[Makerere University]] (where he was president of the Students' Guild),{{citation needed|date=June 2015}} [[Oxford University]] (where he was Overseas Scholar),{{citation needed|date=June 2015}} and [[Harvard Law School]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Olara Otunnu receives Harvard Law School Association Award | url=http://www.law.harvard.edu/news/2007/06/14_otunnu.html | work=News & Events. June 14, 2007 | publisher=Harvard Law School | accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref> (where he was a [[Fulbright Scholar]]).{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}
==Career== Otunnu was appointed by United Nations Secretary-General [[Kofi Annan]] as Special Representative for Children in Armed Conflict on 19 August 1997, taking office on 1 September 1997.<ref name=Press/>
Otunnu ran in 2010 to succeed [[Miria Obote]], wife of former President [[Milton Obote]], as president of the UPC. On 14 May, he defeated her son, Jimmy Akena, at a UPC delegates conference.<ref name="Control"/> UPC nominated him in November 2010 as its presidential candidate.<ref name="Control"/> On election day in 2011, however, he refused to vote, even for himself.<ref name="Control"/> He received 1.58 percent of the vote.<ref>[http://www.electionguide.org/elections/id/2182 Election for President, Republic of Uganda, 18 February 2011, Election Guide - International Foundation for Electoral Systems, accessed 30 June 2015]</ref>
==Awards and nominations== {{BLP sources section|date=June 2015}} Otunnu has received several major International awards, including the Distinguished Service Award from the [[United Nations Association of the United States of America]] (2001); German Africa Prize (2002); the [[Sydney Peace Prize]] (2005); and the Global Award for Outstanding Contribution to Human Rights (India, 2006). In 2007, he received the Harvard Law School Association Award, presented<ref>{{cite web |last=Kagan | first=Elena | title=Questionnaire For Nominee for the Supreme Court| url=http://www.fed-soc.org/docLib/20100518_ElenaKaganPublicQuestionnaire.pdf|work=Bipartisan questionnaire by Senate Judiciary Committee chairman Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.) and Ranking Member Jeff Sessions (R-Ala.)|publisher=United States Senate Judiciary Committee|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119070833/http://www.fed-soc.org/docLib/20100518_ElenaKaganPublicQuestionnaire.pdf|archivedate=19 January 2012 |deadurl=y |accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref> by its president<ref>{{cite web|last=Hébert|first=Jay H.|title=Report of the President, 2006–2008|url=http://law.harvard.edu/alumni/hls-community/report-of-the-president,-2006-2008.html|work=Speech|publisher=Harvard Law School Association|accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref> Jay H. Hebert and [[Elena Kagan]] (an [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Associate Justice of the U.S. Supreme Court – Elena Kagan|url=http://judiciary.senate.gov/nominations/SupremeCourt/KaganIndex.cfm|work=Nominations & Confirmations|publisher=United States Senate Judiciary Committee|accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref>
